# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-storage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-storage/api-storage] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] The **`Storage`** interface of the Web Storage API provides access to a particular domain's session or local storage.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] It allows, for example, the addition, modification, or deletion of stored data items.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] To manipulate, for instance, the session storage for a domain, a call to `Window.sessionStorage` is made; whereas for local storage the call is made to `Window.localStorage`.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] Returns an integer representing the number of data items stored in the `Storage` object.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] When passed a number `n`, this method will return the name of the nth key in the storage.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] When passed a key name, will return that key's value.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] When passed a key name and value, will add that key to the storage, or update that key's value if it already exists.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] When passed a key name, will remove that key from the storage.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] When invoked, will empty all keys out of the storage.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] Here we access a `Storage` object by calling `localStorage`.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] We first test whether the local storage contains data items using `!localStorage.getItem('bgcolor')`.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] If it does, we run a function called `setStyles()` that grabs the data items using `Storage.getItem()` and uses those values to update page styles.
[src:web-storage/api-storage] If it doesn't, we run another function, `populateStorage()`, which uses `Storage.setItem()` to set the item values, then runs `setStyles()`.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] The **`localStorage`** read-only property of the `window` interface allows you to access a `Storage` object for the `Document`'s origin; the stored data is saved across browser sessions.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] `localStorage` is similar to `sessionStorage`, except that while `localStorage` data has no expiration time, `sessionStorage` data gets cleared when the page session ends — that is, when the page is closed.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] A `Storage` object which can be used to access the current origin's local storage space.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] Note that if the user blocks cookies, browsers will probably interpret this as an instruction to prevent the page from persisting data.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] The keys and the values stored with `localStorage` are in the UTF-16 string format.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] As with objects, integer keys are automatically converted to strings.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] `localStorage` data **is specific to the protocol of the document**.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] In particular, for a site loaded over HTTP (e.g., `http://example.com`), `localStorage` returns a different object than `localStorage` for the corresponding site loaded over HTTPS (e.g., `https://example.com`).
[src:web-storage/localstorage] For documents loaded from `file:` URLs (that is, files opened in the browser directly from the user's local filesystem, rather than being served from a web server) the requirements for `localStorage` behavior are undefined and may vary among different browsers.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] In all current browsers, `localStorage` seems to return a different object for each `file:` URL.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] In other words, each `file:` URL seems to have its own unique local-storage area.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] But there are no guarantees about that behavior, so you shouldn't rely on it because, as mentioned above, the requirements for `file:` URLs remain undefined.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] So it's possible that browsers may change their `file:` URL handling for `localStorage` at any time.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] In fact some browsers *have* changed their handling for it over time.
[src:web-storage/localstorage] The following snippet accesses the current domain's local `Storage` object and adds a data item to it using `Storage.setItem()`.
[src:web-storage/sessionstorage] The read-only **`sessionStorage`** property accesses a session `Storage` object for the current origin.
[src:web-storage/sessionstorage] `sessionStorage` is similar to `localStorage`; the difference is that while `localStorage` is partitioned by origin only, `sessionStorage` is partitioned by both origin and browser tabs (top-level browsing contexts).
[src:web-storage/sessionstorage] The data in `sessionStorage` is only kept for the duration of the page session.
[src:web-storage/sessionstorage] A `Storage` object which can be used to access the current origin's session storage space.
[src:web-storage/sessionstorage] The following example autosaves the contents of a text field, and if the browser is refreshed, restores the text field content so that no writing is lost.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] The **`StorageEvent`** interface is implemented by the `storage` event, which is sent to a window when a storage area the window has access to is changed within the context of another document.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns a newly constructed `StorageEvent` object.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns a string with the key for the storage item that was changed.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] The `key` attribute is `null` when the change is caused by the storage `clear()` method.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns a string with the new value of the storage item that was changed.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] This value is `null` when the change has been invoked by storage `clear()` method, or the storage item has been removed from the storage.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns a string with the original value of the storage item that was changed.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] This value is `null` when the storage item has been newly added and therefore doesn't have any previous value.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns a `Storage` object that represents the storage object that was affected.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Returns string with the URL of the document whose storage changed.
[src:web-storage/storageevent] Initializes the event in a manner analogous to the similarly-named `initEvent()` method in the DOM Events interfaces.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The **Web Storage API** provides mechanisms by which browsers can store key/value pairs, in a much more intuitive fashion than using cookies.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] These mechanisms are available via the `Window.sessionStorage` and `Window.localStorage` properties.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Accessing one of these will return an instance of a `Storage` object, through which data items can be set, retrieved and removed.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] A different storage object is used for the `sessionStorage` and `localStorage` for each origin — they function and are controlled separately.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] To learn about the amount of storage available using the APIs, and what happens when storage limits are exceeded, see Storage quotas and eviction criteria.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Both `sessionStorage` and `localStorage` in Web Storage are synchronous in nature.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] This means that when data is set, retrieved, or removed from these storage mechanisms, the operations are performed synchronously, blocking the execution of other JavaScript code until the operation is completed.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] This synchronous behavior can potentially affect the performance of the web application, especially if there is a large amount of data being stored or retrieved.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Developers should be cautious when performing operations on `sessionStorage` or `localStorage` that involve a significant amount of data or computationally intensive tasks.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] It is important to optimize code and minimize synchronous operations to prevent blocking the user interface and causing delays in the application's responsiveness.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Asynchronous alternatives, such as IndexedDB, may be more suitable for scenarios where performance is a concern or when dealing with larger datasets.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] These alternatives allow for non-blocking operations, enabling smoother user experiences and better performance in web applications.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Each origin has its own storage — this is true for both web storage and shared storage.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] However, access of third-party (i.e., embedded) code to shared storage depends on its browsing context.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The context in which a third-party code from another origin runs determines the storage access of the third-party code.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Third-party code can be added to another site by injecting it with a `<script>` element or by setting the source of an `<iframe>` to a site that contains third-party code.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The method used for integrating third-party code determines the browsing context of the code.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Allows you to set, retrieve and remove data for a specific domain and storage type (session or local).
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The `storage` event is fired on a document's `Window` object when a storage area changes.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] To illustrate some typical web storage usage, we have created an example, imaginatively called Web Storage Demo.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The landing page provides controls that can be used to customize the color, font and decorative image.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] When you choose different options, the page is instantly updated; in addition your choices are stored in `localStorage`, so that when you leave the page then load it again later on your choices are remembered.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] In addition, we have provided an event output page — if you load this page in another tab, then make changes to your choices in the landing page, you'll see the updated storage information outputted as the `StorageEvent` is fired.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] Private windows, incognito mode, and similarly named privacy browsing options, don't store data like history and cookies.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] In private mode, `localStorage` is treated like `sessionStorage`.
[src:web-storage/web-storage-api] The storage APIs are still available and fully functional, but all data stored in the private window is deleted when the browser or browser tab is closed.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Web storage differs from cookies in some key ways.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Cookies are intended for communication with servers; they are automatically added to all requests and can be accessed by both the server and client-side.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Web storage falls exclusively under the purview of client-side scripting.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Web storage data is not automatically transmitted to the server in every HTTP request, and a web server can't directly write to Web storage.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] However, either of these effects can be achieved with explicit client-side scripts, allowing for fine-tuning the server's desired interaction.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Web storage offers two different storage areas—local storage and session storage—which differ in scope and lifetime.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Data placed in local storage is per origin—the combination of protocol, host name, and port number as defined in the same-origin policy.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] The data is available to all scripts loaded from pages from the same origin that previously stored the data and persists after the browser is closed.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] As such, Web storage does not suffer from cookie Weak Integrity and Weak Confidentiality issues, described in RFC 6265 sections 8.5 and 8.6.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Session storage is both per-origin and per-instance (per-window or per-tab) and is limited to the lifetime of the instance.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Session storage is intended to allow separate instances of the same web app to run in different windows without interfering with each other, a use case that's not well supported by cookies.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Web storage provides a better programmatic interface than cookies because it exposes an associative array data model where the keys and values are both strings.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Browsers that support web storage have the global objects `sessionStorage` and `localStorage` declared at the window level.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Only strings can be stored via the Storage API.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Attempting to store a different data type will result in an automatic conversion into a string in most browsers.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Conversion into JSON, however, allows for effective storage of JavaScript objects.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] "DOM storage" has also been a commonly used name, though it is becoming less so; for example the "DOM Storage" web articles of the Mozilla and Microsoft developer sites have been replaced with "Web Storage" articles.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] The "DOM" in DOM storage does not literally refer to the Document Object Model.
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Storage of web storage objects is enabled by default in current versions of all supporting web browsers, with browser vendors providing ways for users natively to enable or disable web storage, or clear the web storage "cache".
[src:web-storage/web-storage] Similar controls over web storage are also available through 3rd party browser extensions.
